author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix #34 - don’t coerce to numbers.
body:
Histograms do not require numeric input in general; they merely require ordinal
input and ordinal thresholds for binning. Thus, we were being overly-strict by
coercing everything to numbers.

This also fixes a bug where the Freedman–Diaconis threshold sorted the input
array of values, rather than sorting a copy of the input.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix #24.
body:
If an axis transition interrupts an earlier axis transition, the new transition
will see the exiting ticks for the old transition. If the axis is ordinal, the
position of these ticks may be undefined for both the old and new scale, which
would result in an invalid transform such as `translate(NaN,0)`.

If the new scale’s position for an exiting tick is undefined (as is always the
case with ordinal scales), rather than falling back to the old scale (which may
also be undefined), we simply use the tick’s current transform so that it fades
out in-place.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Rendering improvements!
body:
Offset the axis by a half-pixel so that single-pixel lines exactly cover whole
pixels when the tick position is an integer. This obviates the need for the
crispEdges shape-rendering style when used in conjunction with scale.rangeRound,
and improves the default appearance even without, as long as the axis origin is
at integer coordinates. This is especially noticeable in Safari, where crisp
rendering of single-pixel lines often results in two-pixel lines! Fixes #8.

Use presentation attributes rather than styles to apply the default appearance.
This makes it easier to override the styles using CSS, since any CSS rules will
take precedence of the presentation attributes. Fixes d3/d3#2102.

Extend the default appearance with additional presentation attributes: the
default font is now 10px sans-serif; the domain path and tick lines are now
stroked rather than filled. Fixes #7. Since these are attributes and not styles,
you can easily override the default appearance using CSS. (You can also use
post-selection, as always, to modify the axis.)

This commit also cleans up the axis rendering logic and fixes the transition of
entering ticks: they were previously transitioning in from a tick size of zero,
in addition to fading in. Now they just fade in.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Remove axis.orient.
body:
Instead, construct the axis directly with the given orientation.

This change has several motivations. First, you can’t transition between
orientations, so a mutable orientation makes a false implication. Second, you
should always set an orientation explicitly; relying on the default bottom
orientation made code less clear. Third, symbols for setting orientation are
verbose (axis.orient(axisOrientLeft)) compared to strings (axis.orient("left")),
and especially compared to a dedicated constructor (axisLeft).

Orientation symbols had little value anyway, given that you couldn’t specify a
custom orientation, or save code by eliminating unused orientations.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix #15.
body:
You can clear the brush selection programmatically during a brush gesture, so
the code should not assume that the selection is defined.

Also, you can set the brush selection programmatically during a start event (or
via a timer), so the end event handler must observe the current selection rather
than the selection captured at the gesture’s start.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix brush.move during a brush gesture.
body:
The brush captures the selection at the start of a brush gesture. If the
selection is set programatically by brush.move during a brush gesture, the
captured reference can be different than the brush’s new selection! Now we
always use the element’s current brush selection.

In addition, the brush no longer modifies the selection in-place. If a caller
keeps a reference to the brush selection, it will no longer be affected.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix for more unusual number formats.
body:
According to the CSS Values specification:

> a number is either an integer, or zero or more decimal digits followed by a
> dot (.) followed by one or more decimal digits and optionally an exponent
> composed of "e" or "E" and an integer… the first character of a number may be
> immediately preceded by - or + to indicate the number’s sign.

https://drafts.csswg.org/css-values-3/#numbers

Fixes #31.

body:
CSS has no way of expressing an unset channel, and so for example “transparent”
is defined arbitrarily as rgba(0, 0, 0, 0). This module, in contrast, uses NaN
channels to distinguish a channel that is unset. Therefore when parsing CSS
color specifiers, we must record the unset channels (such as the hue being
undefined when the color is black).

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix #14 - parse rgba and hsla.
body:
All color spaces now have an “opacity” channel in [0,1]. This is primarily
useful because computed styles often have an alpha component, such as the
default transparent background. Soon, d3-interpolate will be able to interpolate
such RGBA colors automatically!

This commit also standardizes the serialization of colors according to the CSS
Object Model specification, which says to use rgb(R, G, B) when alpha is 1 and
rgba(R, G, B, A) otherwise. This is slightly more verbose than hexadecimal, but
means rgb and rgba colors can be formatted similarly.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Consolidate interdependent files.
body:
There’s a circular relationship between the generic color parser and the rgb and
hsl constructors: the color parser instantiates an rgb or hsl color with the
parsed channel values, and the rgb and hsl constructors (when called with a
single argument) applies the color parser to first create an RGB color.

There’s also a circular relationship between the Lab and HCL color spaces, since
the latter is a cylindrical transformation of the former.

Some module loaders (notably Babel; see #22) apparently cannot handle circular
dependencies between files. So now the files are merged.

author: Philippe Rivière
subject: voronoi.neighbors
body:
Returns an iterable over the indexes of the cells that share a common edge with the specified cell *i*. Voronoi neighbors are always neighbors on the Delaunay graph, but the converse is false when the common edge has been clipped out by the Voronoi diagram’s viewport.

fixes https://github.com/d3/d3-delaunay/issues/96

This returns immediately in the general case — and it's more accurate in the degenerate cases; and less code!

For 0, 1, 2 points, and for collinear points:

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Workaround Safari optimizer bug.
body:
It appears that Safari optimizes away the arguments when they are passed to
dispatch.apply; the fix is to inline dispatch.apply in dispatch.call. I was
tempted to use slice.call(arguments, 2) here, and that works, but it also
impedes any optimization as described here:

https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Functions/arguments

I can’t know for sure whether this completely avoids the Safari bug, but it at
least passes the test case here:

author: Philippe Rivière
subject: Incorrect decoding of local dates in Safari. (#53)
body:
instead of treating `new Date("2018-04-25T11:00")` as a local date, Safari parses it as a UTC date and returns it with the tz difference added. This fix detects the situation by checking TWO local dates (one in winter, one in summer) which should return hour 0, and if one of them is not 0 it's the Safari bug.

In that case, and if the date string that is passed is local (no "Z"), and has a time ("T"), we switch to the "2019/09/02 11:00" format, which Safari handles correctly.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Default easing modes.
body:
Is it easeElasticIn or easeElasticOut? I can never remember. And it’s tedious to
type “InOut” when I want something simple like linear easing. This commit
removes easeLinearIn, easeLinearOut and easeLinearInOut; they’re all the same,
so it’s just easeLinear now. The new aliases are as follows:

    easeQuad    ↦ easeQuadInOut
    easeCubic   ↦ easeCubicInOut
    easePoly    ↦ easePolyInOut
    easeSin     ↦ easeSinInOut
    easeExp     ↦ easeExpInOut
    easeCircle  ↦ easeCircleInOut
    easeBounce  ↦ easeBounceOut
    easeBack    ↦ easeBackInOut
    easeElastic ↦ easeElasticOut

Thus, the default is typically in-out, except bounce and elastic which use out.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fox #13 - adopt an easing interface.
body:
Rather than expose bare easing functions, this module now exports instances of
an easing interface: object.ease(t). For example:

    var te = d3.easeCubicIn(t); // BEFORE
    var te = d3.easeCubicIn.ease(t); // AFTER

The primary motivation of this change is to allow D3 transitions to differ-
entiate between an easing type and a function that returns an easing type, as
when the easing type should be determined separately for each selected element.
Also, it means you can use a class to implement a configurable easing type, if
you want, rather than a closure.

This commit also changes how optional parameters are specified for configurable
easing types. Rather than binding optional arguments to the easing function,
create a new instance using method chaining. For example, to create a cubic
easing instance using generic polynomial easing:

    var cubicIn = d3.easeBind(d3.easePolyIn, 3); // BEFORE
    var cubicIn = d3.easePolyIn.exponent(3); // AFTER

Equivalently, to call the function directly:

    var te = d3.easePolyIn(t, 3); // BEFORE
    var te = d3.easePolyIn.exponent(3).ease(t); // AFTER

By giving the parameters explicit names, usage is now self-documenting! Also, we
can eliminate d3.easeBind and easing functions are slightly faster.

Rather than storing separate state for the nodes’ fixed positions, just use the
fx and fy properties on the nodes themselves. This is more similar to the 3.x
API which used node.fixed (and node.px, node.py to store the previous position).
This eliminates the need to expose additional APIs for getting, setting,
clearing and iterating over the fixed positions.

Fixes #35.

default link strength be inversely proportional to the number of links for the
source and the target. This way, if the source or target is heavily connected,
the strength of the link is reduced. However, we still bias the application of
the link such that the less-connected of the two nodes is moved more.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Add simulation.alphaTarget.
body:
This lets you set the “desired” alpha for the simulation, and have the
simulation smoothly interpolate towards the desired value. By default, the
target value is zero, such that the simulation cools. However, by setting it to
a non-zero value, such as during a drag interaction, you can also use it to have
the simulation heat. Fixes #26.

This commit also changes simulation.restart so that it no longer resets the
alpha to one, and changes the meaning of simulation.alphaDecay. The new default
alphaDecay now cause the simulation to end after 300 ticks, instead of 345.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Process collisions serially.
body:
It’s tempting to do them independently (in parallel), but this makes convergence
much slower. We’re now moving nodes while they’re in the quadtree, which means
we could miss a few collisions; but since the tree is rebuilt on each iteration
that should probably be fine.

This reverts part of 95354e8470e946ae445a45fd78a4166107d470ea, though it retains
the area-biased resolution and the performance improvements.

 src/collide.js | 29 ++++++++++-------------------
 1 file changed, 10 insertions(+), 19 deletions(-)

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Improve collision detection.
body:
Fix #25. We now resolve collisions for all nodes independently, rather than
moving one node at a time. And since we’re not mutating the quadtree while
resolving, the quadtree can now store the maximum radius for each quadrant,
accelerating search! We can also optimize resolution a little bit since now
resolutions are always symmetric.

Collision resolutions are now biased so that the acceleration is inversely
proportional to the circle’s area, such that larger circles (which are more
likely to overlap many small circles) are more stable.

Also: only jiggle if two circles are overlapping.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix #20 - simulation.tick now returns boolean.
body:
This changes simulation.tick to always advance the simulation one step,
regardless of the current value of alpha and alphaMin. If alpha is less than
alphaMin after this step, simulation.tick returns true, indicating that the
simulation can be safely ended.

Furthermore, simulation.tick no longer dispatches a tick event; the tick event
is only dispatched by the simulation’s internal timer. This is now consistent
with simulation.stop, which likewise does not dispatch an end event; the end
event is only dispatched when the simulation’s internal timer stops.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Deterministic initialization!
body:
Rather than initialize the node positions randomly, use a phyllotaxis. This is
just as good, and means the resulting behavior will be deterministic as long as
no nodes are exactly coincident.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix #18 - allow manual ticking.
body:
Calling simulation.stop no longer resets the alpha, so a subsequent call to
simulation.start now resumes the simulation, and you can call simulation.tick to
run the simulation manually.

This commit also removes the start event. There’s not much of a point to the
start event since it’s impossible to listen for it in the normal case: the event
is dispatched during the construction of the simulation before any listeners can
be registered. Even in other cases, the simulation is always restarted manually,
so you could always notify a listener manually at the same time. Furthermore,
supporting a start event would require us to track whether the timer is running,
so it’s simpler to just leave it out. (And lastly, eliminating the start event
avoids some confusion about the relationship between simulation.stop and the end
event, which are unrelated!)

Lastly, simplify the recalculation of the current iteration when changing the
alpha decay rate constant.

subject: Improvements.
body:

they behave more like other configurable objects in D3 (though less like curves,
easing functions and interpolators).

Fix #9 - forces now have a dedicated interface rather than just being beforetick
listeners. This allows forces to be re-initialized when the nodes change.

Fix #10 - d3.forcePosition now initializes node positions and velocities.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix #14 - format negative zero as zero.
body:
Negative zero is a construct of IEEE 754 floating point, not a mathematical
concept that (most) humans should care about. And since you may see tick values
that are very small negative numbers due to limited precision, such as -8e-17,
it’s helpful to format these as zero (“0.00”), not negative zero (“-0.00”).

author: Desmond Cheong Zhi Xi
subject: Update README section on Projection api
body:
Add a clarification in the README about using the center() method
for Projections. Developers used to the WGS 84
(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System#WGS84)
reference system that's used by the GPS are likely to default to
specifying latitude before longitude. This can lead to unexpected
behaviours. I believe that making the longitude-first ordering
explicit would reduce the occurence of errors.

author: Philippe Rivière
subject: Proper clipping of degenerate polygons: instead of adding epsilons at the "clipcircle" stage, we pass an explicit message in coordinate z that this point should not be mixed with the previous point, and add the epsilons later, at the "rejoin" stage. Closes #196 and https://github.com/vega/vega/issues/2572

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix default precision.
body:
I forgot that the projection precision is specified in area (square pixels), not
angle (radians), since we use the Visvalingham metric. That also means we can’t
use the projection precision for the generated clip circle.

This commit introduces an image-based test to compare v4 and v3.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix #32 - add d3.geoTransform.
body:
The new implementation is faster: rather than each method being implemented as a
closure, it defines a factory method for creating transform instances.

This also removes d3.geoPath’s fallback projection stream when path.projection
is passed a function rather than something that exposes a stream method. If you
want a projection that uses resampling, use d3.geoProjection.

author: Robin Houston
subject: Avoid an avoidable sqrt()
body:
Since the values that had been divided by scale = sqrt(dc) are
only being used in pairs, we can avoid the square root and just
divide by dc instead.

This should help with the precision, marginally, I hope.

author: Robin Houston
subject: New place() function that avoids overlaps
body:
The old place(a, b, c) function would sometimes place c so it overlapped
with a and/or b, if c had a much larger radius than a and b.

This version doesn’t seem to.

As per discussion on #111.

This commit also updates the tests in find-place-bugs.js to
use the new function, and updates the intersection test in
siblings-test.js to match

Note that flare-test.js fails. I haven’t investigated why: I hope it is simply
a result of the changes in numerical precision causing slightly different
circle placements.

subject: Optimize.
body:
Fix computation of linear distance along the front chain. We can then optimize
by reusing the distance computed during traversal.

Note: the computed linear distance is under-estimated when there are gaps (non-
tangent adjacent circles) in the front chain. This state may occur temporarily
before a circle is placed, but it doesn’t seem to interfere with the algorithm.

chain to find the closest intersecting circle, initialize the traversed distance
using the radius of the two tangent circles.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Checkpoint new hierarchy operator.
body:
I want to support generating hierarchical layouts from either tabular or
hierarchical data, and I want to decouple the conversion of tabular data to
hierarchical data from the hierarchical layout. Also, this should present a
cleaner interface for updating a layout without needing to reconvert the data.

I need better names for d3.hierarchy (which organizes tabular data into a node
tree) and d3.hierarchy2 (which converts raw hierarchical data to a node tree).

author: Waldir Pimenta
subject: interpolateString: clarify docs
body:
The example paragraph for `interpolateString` was worded ambiguously ("The remaining static parts of the string", without specifying which string is being talked about); so unless one had already grasped how the function is supposed to work from the abstract description in the paragraphs above, the interpolation result would be surprising and unclear. The documentation thus fails "bottom-up" learners (i.e. those who learn best by example).

This change is a proposed clarification of the example paragraph by explicitly mentioning the *b* string.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Ignore properties of b not in a.
body:
Previously, the implementation of d3.interpolate{Array,Object} were not
consistent with their documentation, which described how elements or properties
in a but not in b were ignored. This commit changes the implementation to ignore
those properties as intended, such that the final result of the interpolation is
more consistent with the specified end value b.

Fixes #19. Fixes #20.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Better behavior for booleans.
body:
Previously, booleans would be coerced to a number, and interpolated as such.
That seemed a bit magical, so now the constant target value is returned instead,
just as null and undefined are handled. This commit also removes the coerce-to-
number behavior for objects, which no longer seems necessary.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Replace d3.interpolateBind with named parameters.
body:
Rather than have interpolators take optional arguments, and then require
d3-scale to bind those optional arguments, configurable interpolators (of which
cubehelix is the only one, so far) now expose named configuration methods.

    var i = d3.interpolateCubehelix("red", "blue", 3); // BEFORE
    var i = d3.interpolateCubehelix.gamma(3)("red", "blue"); // AFTER

This makes the usage of optional parameters self-documenting.

Related d3/d3-ease#13.

author: Philippe Rivière
subject: prevent an infinite loop
body:
The situation happens in force simulations when a point is horribly far (maybe because of a programming error, or because we set the wrong parameters on an experimental force). Then forceCollide calls quadtree(nodes, x,,y), which tries to cover by repeatedly doubling z=0. This ends up crashing the browser.

author: Parcly Taxel
subject: Expand domain of randomWeibull to all real numbers
body:
The structure of the algorithm for generating Weibull random variates
allows generating Fréchet variates "for free" by providing a negative
shape parameter. The Gumbel distribution is what results at zero shape
parameter, and fills in the gap between the Weibull and Fréchet regimes.
In this way, no shape parameter is wasted.

randomWeibull now accepts both location and scale parameters, mimicking
randomCauchy and randomLogistic.

See https://observablehq.com/@parcly-taxel/frechet-gumbel-weibull

guaranteed finite if source() is in [0,1), which is already required.

subject: Introduce O(log log n) binomial generator
body:
The current binomial generator takes O(n) time. The new generator, based
on Ahrens and Dieter (1974), takes less than 0.25 seconds to generate
10^5 variates at n = 10^12, and remains fast for smaller n.

See also https://observablehq.com/@parcly-taxel/faster-binomial-variates

author: Parcly Taxel
subject: Allow 0 as a parameter for randomGeometric
body:
Logically, a geometric(0) variate always fails, so it always returns
infinity. This commit expands the domain of randomGeometric() to
that case, which will make the implementation of a future binomial
generator a little easier.

log1p() is also used for higher accuracy.

author: Alex Van Camp
subject: allow loading in browser via es modules
body:
Browser implementations of `import` do not assume a `.js` file extension. As such, the relative imports used in `d3-random` all fail with a 404, because the actual files on disk _do_ have `.js` extensions, while the corresponding `import` statements in the code do not.

This fixes this issue by simply adding explicit `.js` extensions to all `import` statements, thereby allowing the native browser implementations of ES Modules to successfully load these imports.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix #65 - coerce domain to date.
body:
Previously it was possible to set a time scale’s domain to valid numbers but not
valid dates: the allowable range for Number is much larger than the allowable
range for Date. (The latter is only ±8.64e15!) By coercing the domain to date,
we avoid a nearly-infinite loop when trying to compute ticks.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Use inline style value, if present.
body:
Rather than always returning the computed style value, selection.style now
favors the inline value, if present, and only falls back to the computed value
if an inline value is not present.

By not computing the style value in the common case where an inline style is
present, this is faster, but more importantly it is more predictable, since a
computed value can be surprisingly different from an inline value, such as when
the inline value is specified as a percentage.

This change is especially useful for transition.style, d3/d3-transition#47, so
that you can control the starting style value of a transition.

observe it even if it is null.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Use a parallel array to store parent nodes.
body:
Instead of decorating each group with a _parent, keep a parallel array of
parents. This is typically more efficient, and has the nice property that a
parents array can be shared when creating a subselection, since the parents are
immutable. (It’s also easier to test and inspect.)

Note that this means you can no longer access nodes._parent in a selection
function, but this was a private API.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Implement polyfills; fix enter & exit linking.
body:
Polyfills are now implemented for mouseenter events, mouseleave events,
element.matches and CustomEvent. The CustomEvent polyfill is implemented lazily
on a per-window basis, whereas the others are only implemented once for the
global document (and thus are typically only available in browsers, and not
within the Node environment).

In addition, this commit changes how the update selection is linked to the enter
and update selections. Rather than linking each group, only the top-level update
selection object now has a reference to the enter selection and exit selection.
(Likewise, the enter selection now has a reference back to the update selection,
rather than linking from each enter group.)

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Sticky enter and exit selections. Fixes #22.
body:
Rather than create new enter and exit selections whenever joining to data, we
lazily create them the first time they are accessed, and then subsequently
update them in-place. Thus, the enter, update and exit selections are now all
modified in-place when joining to data.

A selection now keeps a reference to its lazily-constructed enter (_e) and exit
(_x) selections. The old reference from an enter selection group back to its
corresponding update selection group (group.update) is replaced with a reference
to the update selection (_u) from the enter selection.

author: Joseph Mansfield
subject: Clamp acos when computing rounded corners
body:
Due to floating point imprecision, computing the angle between two
vectors with `theta = acos((a . b) / sqrt(|a||b|))` gives NaN when
`(a . b) / sqrt(|a||b|)` is outside the domain of `acos`. We can
use a clamped version of acos to avoid this, which clamps to
[-1, 1].

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Use a default alpha of 0.5 for Catmull–Rom.
body:
Centripetal splines have some nice properties: curves do not form cusps or self-
intersections within curve segments. And, since Catmull–Rom with α = 0 is
equivalent to cardinal with tension = 0, curve(catmullRom) and curve(cardinal)
were previously equivalent. Now curve(catmullRom) is different and better!

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Wait for three points with open cubic Hermite splines.
body:
Even though we know the location of the first output point after receiving two
input points, we don’t know the first segment until we’ve received four input
points. Rather than generate the first output point after receiving two points
and doing nothing with upon receiving the third point, we now do nothing after
receiving two points and generate the first output point upon receiving the
third point.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix #10 - infinite loop in d3.timeHour.range.
body:
In Chrome and V8, date.setMinutes(0, 0, 0) loses an hour at the start of
daylight savings, rather than rounding down to the start of the current hour:

    var date = new Date(1478419200000); // Sun Nov 06 2016 01:00:00 GMT-0700 (PDT)
    date.setTime(+date + 1 * 36e5); // Sun Nov 06 2016 01:00:00 GMT-0800 (PST)
    date.setMinutes(0, 0, 0); // Sun Nov 06 2016 01:00:00 GMT-0700 (PDT)

Rather than rely on setMinutes, the hour, minute and second local time intervals
now round manually while observing the timezone offset.

author: Philippe Rivière
subject: French format for %c datetime
body:
locale.format("%c")(new Date()) returns "mardi, le  9 juin 2020, 18:58:57", which is weird.

I can't find a very clear spec, but:
~~~{js}
new Intl.DateTimeFormat('fr-FR', {
  weekday: 'long',
  year: 'numeric',
  month: 'long',
  day: 'numeric',
  hour: 'numeric',
  minute: 'numeric',
  second: 'numeric'
}).format(new Date())
~~~

returns "mardi 9 juin 2020 à 19:09:23", which definitely sounds better.

(This commit returns "mardi  9 juin 2020 à 19:09:23" with an extra space.)

author: Ryusei Yamaguchi
subject: Correct ja-JP time format
body:
- The old format of date time `"%Y %b %e %a %X"` generates strings like `2020 3月 10 火 15:20:22`, which is not correct. The date part of them should be either `2020/03/10` using slashes as separators or `2020年3月10日` using 年 (year), 月 (month) and 日 (day) as suffixes. Using suffixes partly should be avoided.
- Month names are replaced with numeric notation with kanji suffix because these names are obsolete and mostly used for Chinese luni-solar calendar.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: More sensible default en-US locale.
body:
The previous default en-US locale used 24-hour time. This matched the default
behavior of the `date` command on macOS, but isn’t the local convention. These
new definitions are based on the behavior of date.toLocale{,Date,Time}String in
Chrome, Node and Firefox. (Safari is a little different.)

    %C: "%a %b %e %X %Y" ↦ "%x, %X"
    %x: "%H:%M:%S" ↦ "%-I:%M:%S %p"
    %X: "%m/%d/%Y" ↦ "%-m/%-d/%Y"

Fixes #19.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Add comment regarding delay calculation.
body:
In the common case, we assume that the clock has not advanced significantly
since we woke when scheduing the next sleep timer. Since the clock can only move
forward, we only need to check the clock if we actually schedule a timer, and
not if we’ll use an animation frame.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix #27 - inaccurate timeout delay.
body:
If timers are expensive, then by the time we sleep, the current time may have
advanced substantially from the `clockNow` computed on wake. Therefore we must
recompute the current time before scheduling the timeout.

 src/timer.js | 4 ++--

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Record clock before sleeping.
body:
Fixes #17. The poke interval was relying on the wake callback to record the
last-seen clock time, clockLast. If no timers were run before sleeping (such as
when no timers are run immediately on load, but timers are scheduled during a
timeout), clockLast was still its initial value, zero. Now we set clockLast to
clockNow before scheduling the poke interval, so that it detects skew relative
to the time the poke interval was started.

 src/timer.js | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Don’t rely on requestAnimationFrame timestamp.
body:
Instead, always call performance.now (or Date.now) to retrieve the current time.
The performance cost of doing this is negligble since this happens at most once
per animation frame, and it simplifies the logic, fixing #16.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Fix #6 - a slow poke for paused animations.
body:
In some browsers, requestAnimationFrame is paused in background tabs. This can
cause the page to hang when returned to the foreground, as when a huge queue of
chained transitions (d3/d3-transition#29 mbostock/d3#2211) builds up. So we now
wake up every five seconds to flush the queue.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Add d3.now().
body:
This method returns the current high-resolution time, using performance.now
where available. Furthermore, it is consistent during an animation frame or
while handling event, ensuring that any scheduled timers (or transitions!) have
consistent timing.

Since the current time is now available by calling d3.now(), the timer callbacks
no longer receive a second argument; they only receive the elapsed time.

Fixes d3/d3-transition#18.

This makes the mechanism for canceling a timer from inside its callback the same
as from outside, rather than the former using `this.stop()`. (This also
simplifies our implementation slightly.)

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Hide private fields; rename reset to restart.
body:
Rather than storing the timer linked list on the timer objects, we now store a
map of task-by-id and reference the task by timer.id. This is similar to how
setTimeout and setInterval work (although we still provide a convenient timer
object with methods rather than just a long identifier).

The reset method has been renamed to restart, and you can now restart a timer
that has been stopped. If the timer was stopped, this is equivalent to creating
a new timer in that the task is put at the end of the queue.

Also, fix instanceof timer.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Simplify.
body:
Rather than remove the timer from the queue synchronously, we clear its callback
and remove it on the next tick. This means we can use a singly-linked list.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Timer, Stop!
body:
Rather than stopping timers by having the callback return true, timer(…) now
returns a timer object with a stop method. Thus, you can now stop a timer
synchronously outside of its callback, rather than having to wait until the
timer is next called back. You can also reset a timer (changing its start time
or callback) externally, too. Fixes #5.

This commit also wraps timer execution with a try-finally block, fixing #4.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Use inline style value, if present.
body:
Rather than always starting from the computed style value, transition.style now
favors the inline value, if present, and only falls back to the computed value
if an inline value is not present.

By not computing the style value in the common case where an inline style is
present, this is faster, but more importantly it is more predictable since a
computed value can be surprisingly different from an inline value, such as when
the inline value is specified as a percentage.

Related d3/d3-selection#120. Fixes #47.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Stop immediately after last tick, if possible.
body:
Rather than defer stop to the end of the current frame, we now stop the
transition immediately after its last tick, as before. If a tween or an end
event listener throws an error, the transition will (eventually) be cleaned up
on a following tick.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Protect against errors.
body:
If a transition throws an error on start, we no longer repeatedly restart the
transition at every frame. Instead, we silently terminate the transition on the
next frame. If a transition throws an error on end, we no longer run the
transition forever at t=1. Instead, we silently terminate the transition at the
end of the current frame (or a subsequent frame, if an error is thrown by
another timer).

Fixes #48 #55.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: A specialized interpolator.
body:
The target value for transition.{attr,style} should always be a number, a color
or a string; therefore, we can use a specialized interpolator that is more
efficient than d3.interpolator.

This commit also removes coercion of the target attribute or style value to a
string; that’s not done in selection.{attr,style}, so it should be necessary
here, and it’s more efficient if we can optimize numeric target values, too.

scheduled, so as to avoid changes during a start event (due to changes being
copy-on-write). However, you should still be allowed to change the OTHER event
listeners (interrupt and end) before the transition starts; in particular,
transition.remove should be allowed during a start event!

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Copy-on-write!
body:
If the next node in a transition shares state with the previous node, as is
often the case due to transition method applying to the entire selection, then
we can reuse the state rather than creating separate state for each node.

This commit also starts to enforce restrictions on when transition state can be
modified; transition state should only be modified before the transition starts,
or in the case of delay or event listeners, before the transition is scheduled!

Related #24 #25 #27 #28.

author: Robin Houston
subject: Use touches rather than changedTouches in touchstarted
body:
It seems that the behaviour of Chrome on Android differs from the
behaviour of Safari on iOS in the following respect: when a multitouch
event is initiated by touching two or more fingers to the screen
near-simultaneously, iOS Safari will fire a single touchstart event
that includes all the touches (as both event.touches and event.changedTouches)
whereas Android Chrome will fire a sequence of touchstart events:

- one with touches.length == 1 and changedTouches.length == 1
- followed by one with touches.length == 2 and changedTouches.length == 1

In other words, the behaviour on Android Chrome when the screen is
touched with two fingers simultaneously is the same as the behaviour
on iOS Safari when you touch it first with one finger and then a second.

The change in PR #169 makes it possible to ignore single-touch gestures
on iOS Safari, but this fails on Android Chrome because the first touch
is never recorded. When the second touch is processed, the changedTouches
array contains only the second touch.

This commit changes the behaviour of the touchstarted handler to consider
all the touches in the event, rather than just the new touches.

subject: Fix wheel after mousemove.
body:
If the mouse moves to a new point, we should immediately compute the new
corresponding location. Also, there’s no reason to track separate points and
locations for the mouse and the wheel, since we assume they correspond to the
same input device.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Add zoom.translateExtent.
body:
The translate extent, unlike the scale extent, isn’t a simple constraint on t_x
and t_y; instead, it is the extent of the viewable world. The zoom behavior can
then limit the transform such that the extent of the view (zoom.extent) is
always within the extent of the world.

This also replaces zoom.size with zoom.extent so that you can tell the zoom
behavior the extent of the viewport, rather than assuming the top-left corner is
always at [0, 0].

Fixes #25. Related d3/d3#1084 d3/d3#1299.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Don’t enforce scale extent on zoom.transform.
body:
Restoring the scale to an allowed value requires defining how to change the
translation accordingly. Previously, we preserved the view center (as defined by
zoom.size), which is consistent with zoom.scale{By,To}, but feels somewhat
arbtirary and complicated. Seems simpler to do nothing.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Remove zoom.center.
body:
The problem is that it’s too vague or specific a concept. Does it apply just to
wheeling, or also to double clicks? Does it affect zoom transitions and clamping
by the scale extent?

Originally this feature was conceived of letting you zoom in and out, but not
translate. But it doesn’t work well for this, because it doesn’t work for touch,
and because you still have to unregister the dblclick and mousedown listeners. I
need to design a more general replacement for this, such as a hook for
constraining the zoom transform arbitrarily.

author: Mike Bostock
subject: Distinguish “target” and “current” views.
body:
The target view represents the programmatically-set view; the current view
represents the active element’s view as displayed, as determined by the last
application of the zoom behavior and subsequently modified through interaction.

The target view is NOT updated through interaction. This is because the zoom
behavior may be applied to multiple elements, and the current view of each
element may differ; it is only set programmatically.

Related #3.
